<TD WIDTH="382">

<FONT FACE="Arial, Verdana, Sans Serif" SIZE="-1">

<P ALIGN="left"><B><FONT SIZE="+0"><I>Chlorosplenium chlora</I></FONT></B></P>

<P><FONT SIZE="-2">[ <A HREF="taxonomy.html#ascomycota">Ascomycota</A>&nbsp;>&nbsp;<A HREF="taxonomy.html#helotiales">Helotiales</A>&nbsp;>&nbsp;<A HREF="taxonomy.html#dermateaceae">Dermateaceae</A>&nbsp;>&nbsp;Chlorosplenium ... ]</FONT></P>

<P>by <A HREF="contributors.html#kuo">Michael Kuo</A></P>

<P>This tiny <A HREF="cups.html">cup fungus</A> grows on the well-rotted, barkless wood
of hardwoods or conifers in eastern North America. Its colors range from yellow to olive green, and are strongest on the undersurface; the fertile upper surface tends to become pale and nearly whitish as the cups mature. Under the microscope, <I>Chlorosplenium chlora</I> features fairly small, fusiform-ish spores, and filiform paraphyses.</P>

<P><I>Chlorosplenium hypochlora</I> is identical to the naked eye, but features longer spores. Also compare <I>Chlorosplenium chlora</I> to <A HREF="chlorociboria_aeruginascens.html"><I>Chlorociboria aeruginascens</I></A>, with uniformly greenish blue fruiting bodies, and <A HREF="chlorencoelia_torta.html"><I>Chlorencoelia torta</I></A> and <I>Chlorencoelia versiformis</I>, both of which are somewhat larger and browner.</P>

<P><B>Description:</B></P>

<P>Ecology: <A HREF="glossary.html#saprobe">Saprobic</A> on well-decayed, barkless wood of hardwoods or conifers; growing gregariously to densely gregariously; summer and fall; apparently widely distributed in North America east of the Great Plains. The illustrated and described collection is from Illinois.</P>

<P>Fruiting Body: Cup-shaped at first, becoming flattened or disc-shaped; without a stem; cups 1&ndash;3 mm across; upper surface bald, yellow at first, becoming pale yellow to whitish or grayish, and eventually greenish; undersurface bright yellow, finely and sparsely fibrillose when viewed with a lens; flesh yellowish to greenish, unchanging when sliced.</P>

<P><A HREF="odortaste.html">Odor</A>: Not distinctive.</P>

<P><A HREF="microscope.html">Microscopic Features</A>: Spores 7&ndash;9 x 1&ndash;2 &#181;m; subfusiform or nearly cylindric; smooth; hyaline and biguttulate in KOH. Asci 45&ndash;65 &#181;m long; cylindric; hyaline in KOH; hyaline with a tiny amyloid tip in Melzer's. Paraphyses filiform with subacute or merely rounded apices; 45&ndash;65 x 1&ndash;2 &#181;m. Medullary excipulum elements green in KOH.</P>

<BR>

<P><FONT SIZE="-2"><A HREF="references.html">REFERENCES</A>: (Schweinitz, 1822) M. A. Curtis, 1856. (Fries, 1822; Saccardo, 1889; Dixon, 1974; Beug et al., 2014.) <A HREF="herbarium/index.html">Herb. Kuo</A> 09301502.</FONT></P>

<BR>

<P><I>This site contains no information about the edibility or toxicity of mushrooms.</I></P></P>

</FONT>

</TD>

